[CALCITE-1637] Add mutable equivalents for all relational expressions

[CALCITE-1107] Make SqlSumEmptyIsZeroAggFunction constructor public (Minji Kim)

Close apache/calcite#242

[CALCITE-1448] Add rules to flatten and prune Intersect and Minus

New instances of UnionMergeRule flatten trees of Intersect and Minus
operators into nodes that have more than 2 inputs.

New rules in PruneEmptyRules act on Intersect and Minus that have
empty inputs, either converting them to the empty relational
expression or removing empty inputs.

RelBuilder now allows Minus to have more than 2 inputs.

[CALCITE-1522] Fix error message for SetOp with incompatible args (Jess Balint)

Close apache/calcite#331
[CALCITE-397] "SELECT DISTINCT *" on reflective schema gives ClassCastException at runtime

Fix 'mvn site' on JDK 1.8 and enable in Travis-CI.

Fix several javadoc errors and warnings.

Remove some duplicate package-info.java files.

Remove versions of maven plugins where apache pom already specifies a version.

[CALCITE-1833] User-defined aggregate functions with more than one parameter (hzyuemeng1)

I don't like the fact that SqlUserDefinedAggregateFunction now has a
type factory field. I see why it is necessary - because the
SqlFunction.getParamTypes method does not take a type factory argument -
but we should consider changing it in future.

Close apache/calcite#481
[CALCITE-821] Frameworks gives NPE when FrameworkConfig has no default schema

[CALCITE-1807] Upgrade to Avatica 1.10.0

Includes fix to [CALCITE-1664] CAST('<string>' as TIMESTAMP) adds part of sub-second fraction to the value

Replace uses of DateTimeUtils.GMT_Zone with UTC_ZONE.
[OPTIQ-402] Lattice should create materializations on demand

SCXML-196: The Algorithm for SCXML interpretation requires sets of TransitionTarget instances to be processed.
To conform to the Set equality contract TransitionTarget must implement the equals and hashcode methods.
But in the context of SCXML and the purpose of the algorithm, really only identity based equality should be considered.
The TransitionTarget#id property also could be used, but that would make the API much more awkward to ensure only unique IDs are used, that is: within the context of a single SCXML instance.
Much easier therefore is to just enforce and only support identity based equality.

DRILL-4654: Add new metrics to the MetricRegistry

+ New metrics:
  - drill.queries.enqueued
    number of queries that have been submitted to the drillbit but have
    not started
  - drill.queries.running
    number of running queries for which this drillbit is the foreman
  - drill.queries.completed
    number of completed queries (or cancelled or failed) for which this
    drillbit was the foreman
  - drill.fragments.running
    number of query fragments that are running in the drillbit
  - drill.allocator.root.used
    amount of memory used in bytes by the internal memory allocator
  - drill.allocator.root.peak
    peak amount of memory used in bytes by the internal memory allocator
  - fd.usage
    ratio of used to total file descriptors (on *nix systems)
+ Rename "current" to "used" for RPC allocator current memory usage to
  follow convention
+ Borrow SystemPropertyUtil class from Netty
+ Configure DrillMetrics through system properties
+ Remove unused methods and imports

SSHD-8: Secure the agent socket against race conditions

Binding a UNIX domain socket creates the socket file with the
current umask.  This may permit evil members of the caller's group
to connect to the socket before the listening process can mark it
as accessible only by the owner.

Instead, create a temporary directory that is accessible only to
the owner, and only after the location is locked down, create the
socket within it as a unique random name.

PARQUET-548: Add EncodingStats.

This adds `EncodingStats`, which tracks the number of pages for each encoding, separated into dictionary and data pages. It also adds convenience functions that are useful for dictionary filtering, like `hasDictionaryEncodedPages` and `hasNonDictionaryEncodedPages`.

`EncodingStats` have a unit test in parquet-column and an integration test in parquet-hadoop that writes a file and verifies the stats are present and correct when it is read.

This includes commits from #330 because it updates the dictionary filter. I'll rebase and remove them once it is merged.

git-svn-id: https://google-caja.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@5103 360991c0-9f3b-0410-ba87-8b362a00edf4

Handling hyphens within comments gracefully
<unassigned>

In the renderUnsafe mode, we currently disallow comments that begin with or end
with '-' because of the Html 5 and XML 1 specs.

This causes an IllegalStateException with the message "XML comment unrenderable
because it ends with '-'" to be thrown when parsing some documents:

However, browsers do handle these gracefully and allow these extra hyphens, as
can be seen in the following discussions:
http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/intro/sgmltut.html#h-3.2.4
http://marcorogers.com/blog/08-02-2009/strange-firefox-rendering-bug

This patch modifies comments that begin or end with hyphens or contain
consecutive hyphens, to make them spec-compliant.

Patch from Anupama. Thanks!

Improve error-prone options handling to allow enabling non-default checks and
promoting warnings to errors and errors to warnings.

This CL changes error-prone options handling to make it cleaner, allow users
to enable non-default checks, and allow users to override the built-in severity
level (warning vs. error).

Old-style error-prone flags looked like:
-Xepdisable:<checkName[,checkName...]

New error-prone flags look like:
-Xep:<checkName>[:severity]
where severity is one of {OFF, WARN, ERROR}.  If no severity is provided, then
the default severity is used.

This change retains support for the old-style flags until we can clean
the depot.

Improve algorithm to look for tiles that match a query, to allow inexact matches.

Look for materialized tiles that can be rolled up before creating a tile that is an exact match for the query. If there is a tile that has the right dimensionality but the wrong measures, in the worst case create a new tile with the union of the measures. If there are multiple tiles that can be rolled up, choose the one with the fewest rows.

[GIRAPH-1022] Adaptive out-of-core mechanism for input superstep and graph

Summary: This code adds the ability to adaptively control the out-of-core mechanism for graph data structure at run-time during input/output superstep and computation superstep. Basically, the implemented mechanism monitors the amount of available free memory in a separate thread. If there is not enough memory, the code adjusts the number of partitions in memory, and spills a series of partitions/buffers to disk. Also, if the amount of free memory is more than expected, some of the on-disk partitions are brought back to memory. Additionally, if amount of free memory is marginal, the mechanism mocks the memory usage by gradually bringing partitions to memory.

Decouple out-of-core persistence infrastructure from out-of-core computation

Summary:
This diff proposes the following:
  - The persistence layer is decoupled from out-of-core infrastructure. This way one can simply implement different data accessors for various persistence resources. The persistence layer for reading/writing from/to local file system is implemented in this diff.
  - Previously, out-of-core data were indexed by string literals. This has changed for more flexibility. Now, data are accessible by a more flexible data indexing mechanism, in which a chain of indices are used to address a particular data.
  - With different implementations of data accessor, now there may be more emphasis on having more IO threads. It is important that these IO threads are load-balanced. In this diff, the mechanism to assign partitions to IO threads has changed.
  - All the coolness of Kryo's (de)serialization and RandomAccessFile (in D59277) is included in this diff, all at one place.

QPIDJMS-305 Refactor the SASL Authentication process to remove race

Refactor of the SASL Authenticator and the way it handles failures and
how they are then reported.  Removes a race where an async provider
exception and the exception returned from the connect call can chase
each other and the wrong one gets tracked as the failure cuase.

PARQUET-116: Pass a filter object to user defined predicate in filter2 api

Currently for creating a user defined predicate using the new filter api, no value can be passed to create a dynamic filter at runtime. This reduces the usefulness of the user defined predicate, and meaningful predicates cannot be created. We can add a generic Object value that is passed through the api, which can internally be used in the keep function of the user defined predicate for creating many different types of filters.
For example, in spark sql, we can pass in a list of filter values for a where IN clause query and filter the row values based on that list.

QPIDJMS-346 Pass along any errors from result of unsubscribe calls

When the detach of a recovered durable subscription is received we need
to check that the remote did not indicate that there was an error on the
detach.  If there was then the unsubscribe likely failed and we want to
pass those errors along to the caller of Session#unsubscribe("sub")

also reduce the amount of garbage created in the process.  Also improve
the tag cache to reduce simplify the tag pool such that it doesn't
create any additional garbage on checkout or checkin and optimizes the
checkin process.

ZOOKEEPER-2949: using hostname and port to create SSLEngine

If the server has more than one host name, and serve each host name with different certificates. then the ssl client must provide the server name in the ssl Hello packet, to tell the server which certificate to use.
This is especially important when the client connect to a load balancer with different backend services.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Server_Name_Indication

git-svn-id: https://google-caja.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@3676 360991c0-9f3b-0410-ba87-8b362a00edf4

Turkish i defense in java
http://codereview.appspot.com/6300084

Because of the Turkish 'i', String#toLowerCase etc are unsafe to use.
We have Strings.toLowerCase etc that are safe, but they aren't used
universally.

This patch does:

- rename Strings.toLowerCase etc to Strings.lower etc, so that it's
easier to use a simple grep to find stray uses of the unsafe methods.

- add a shell script tools/codecheck.sh that complains if the unsafe
methods get used.  "ant runtests" will run codecheck.

- fix all uses of the unsafe methods.

- replace hand-coded loops in Strings.lower etc with standard calls
using Locale.ENGLISH, because it's less code to worry about.  This
behaves differently for non-ASCII characters, but we don't care as
long as it's consistent and isn't confused by Turkish 'i' issues.

R=ihab.awad@gmail.com

Created by MOE: http://code.google.com/p/moe-java
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=29564148

GSS Sourcemap Implementation CL #3

This change implements automatic line index and character index
updates during write to the output buffer; it also includes a refactor
work on the code related with buffer.

Inspired by @flan's advice and taking some second thought, I extract
buffer related operations out into a independent class {@code
CodeBuffer} with public APIs. They could be optionally injected into
{@code CodePrinter} where they are used.  Core CodeBuffer APIs are
marked as final to ensure the correct behavior for {@code lineIndex}
and {@code charIndex} and prevent accidental override.

The detailed behaviors for public APIs are documented by {@code
CodeBufferTest}.

Special printer which needs buffer helpers could subclass CodeBuffer
and override some of the APIs. (Example at {@link
TemplateCompactPrinter} and inject into the printer class.)

At last, there are some cleanup work on related visitors to use the
safe APIs when writing out to buffer. For example, the deleteCharAt()
is replaced by deleteLastChar(). Also append(String) is replaced with
append(char) whenever possible.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe

Soy conformance: use standard error reporting infrastructure.

I wrote the Soy conformance framework about 8 months ago when I didn't know much about the Soy codebase. Now that I do, it's time to use standard Soy facilities for AST traversal and error reporting.

This CL changes the SoyConformance interface to be a vacuous subinterface of NodeVisitor. (We still need to have an interface-impl pair because the impl uses protocol buffers, which are annoying to open-source.) The single SoyConformance implementation subclasses an abstract base class that provides an error reporter.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=166488318

soy jbcsrc: Reduce the number of places we reference the soy type system.

The soy type system has a number of places where it gets out of touch with
reality and/or implements slightly looser semantics.  This have been the cause
of much pain.  So instead we limit the number of places that we reference it
and instead rely on our own understanding of the operators.

With this cl we (pretty much) only use the type system for params, data
accesses and literals.  There is probably more to remove but this is the bulk
of it.

Try to make @Provides provisioning more like @Inject provisioning

To do this i created a new BindingImpl + InternalFactory implementation for @Provides methods.  This was mostly modeled off of how ConstructorBindingImpl + ConstructorBindingImpl.Factory work (with ProviderMethod taking the place of ConstructorInjector).  This has the benefit of removing a bunch of overhead when @Provides methods construct their dependencies.

Before this change there is a definite gap in performance between the @Inject and @Provides strategies.  After this change @Provides is actually faster than @Inject constructors.  I believe this is due to the fact that there is no MembersInjector involved and the circular proxy logic is slightly simpler (so i will definitely be looking at this next!).

The overall benefit is simply due to
1. eliminating the ProviderLookup wrappers
2. eliminating the new InternalContext + InjectorImpl.callInContext for each @Provides invocation

For future work i want to look into eliminating more of the object allocations.  Currently there are 31 for this benchmark.  The bare minimum is 5 (because that is how many objects are getting constructed).

This cl saved 22 stack frames (~4 per @Provides method)

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=119864113

Fix issue 723 -- minor optimizations to TypeConverterBindingProcessor.
Description in the bug describes this best:
TypeConverterBindingProcessor has two responsibilities: 1) prepare built-in type
converters for primitives, enums, classes, etc. and 2) process TypeConverter
bindings and register them with the containing injector.

The first responsibility only needs the injector reference, it doesn't need
access to the processor's Errors cache. However, the current implementation
runs in the context of the processor and creates a number of anonymous classes,
and they all contain an implicit reference (this$0) back to the processor. This
can lead to some Errors instances being kept alive longer than necessary by
these anonymous classes, but not a large number.

Changing the prepareBuiltInConverters implementation over to use static methods
that pass the injector as an argument fixes this problem by removing the
implicit reference to the processor, since the anonymous classes are now
created from a static context.

Patch by Stuart McCulloch.  Thanks Stuart!

Making Singleton's creation lock less coarse.

Singleton is defined as a scope which creates no more than one
object per injector. It's highly confusing when you catch a deadlock
between two unrelated injectors due to the same class injection.

Problem is demonstrated using a test that recreates scenario when
one thread injecting class can block other thread to use its own
injector.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=139791656

Better type annotation disambiguation

Given the method signature `void f(java.lang.@A String x);`, `@A` is
unambiguously a type annotation. Currently this isn't handled correctly
because the bound model doesn't distinguish between `java.lang.@A
String` and `@A String`, so if `@A` can target parameters it gets added
to the parameter declaration.

To handle this better, the parser now collects all ambiguous annotations
into the declaration annotation list. In practice, the only case that
changes is method declaration annotations that occur after the formal
type parameter list, e.g. previously `@A` was classified as a type
annotation in `<T> @A void f();`.

Finally, during disambiguation annotations are now only moved from
declarations to types, and never from types to declarations.

adding sanity check when setting the partitioner.
after we read in the existing yaml file, check to see if the declared partitioner
is not RandomPartitioner or the new (as of c* 1.2) Murmur3Partitioner. If it is not,
assume the deployment is _not_ using a default partitioner, but a custom one
(like OPP, BOP, or something else). This way, we don't trash the entire dataset
when this new version of priam is deployed due to differeing partitioners across the ring.

Fixing false assumption in TuneCassandra. Previously, there was logic to guard
against yaml config settings that had been added or removed from different versions. This was tested
by adding a null check to see if the setting existed in the yaml that was read in. Unfortunately,
if a property was commented out in the yaml (yet still compltetly valid as a setting) the entry would
not be present in the map that snakeyaml produced, and hence you could never write out that setting.
Basically this was a poor man's way to avoid branching. Now that we branch in priam, that is no longer necessary.

A framework for using different page signature implementations. Ordinary
MD5 hash of a raw page content is very often unsuitable, when many
near-duplicate pages are crawled.

Now users can select their own page signature implementation, possibly
with better properties than the old one.

Two implementations are provided:

* MD5Signature: backward-compatible with the old schema.

* TextProfileSignature: an example implementation of a signature, which
  gives the same values for near-duplicate pages. Please see Javadoc for
  more information.

This commit changes the CrawlDatum to store page signatures in CrawlDb.
Last modified time field was added, too. Both changes are in preparation
for patches implementing self-adjustable fetch interval.

*mikesamuel/rework-synthetics@2084 | mikesamuel | 2008-08-04 16:51:33 -0800 (Mon, 04 Aug 2008)

Description:

Simplify how synthetics are used in preparation for implementing
Ihab's custom node idea for pluggable code generators.


Goal
====
Ihab pointed out that the current synthetic mechanism combined with
pipelining makes it impossible to make the TCB smaller than all
possible code that a pipeline author could write.

There are a couple existing pipeline stages that generate synthetic
content -- GXP templates for HTML, CSS templates, the HtmlCompiler
code that extracts HTML event handlers.

The goal of this CL is to lay the groundwork for a narrow definition
of synthetic, so that we can have both an extensible pipeline and a
small TCB.


Design
======
Create a few custom nodes with rigorous consistency checks that are
passed through by the DefaultCajaRewriter.

The custom nodes will be part of the TCB, and any user code they
contain must be exposed as children.  At render time, the custom nodes
construct a parse tree of regular node, and delegate rendering to
that.


Material Changes in this CL
===========================
Previously, any node could be marked synthetic.  Now only
FunctionConstructors and Identifiers can.  Since SyntheticNodes.java
now knows about JS node types, I moved it into ...parser.js from
...parser.

Previously there was one rewriter rule that did an expandAll on any
synthetic node.  Now there is one per specific construct that we want
to pass through.

Changed QuasiBuilder so that when it parses a quasiliteral,
identifiers that end in __ are marked synthetic since they are clearly
intentional rules violations.

Added /*@synthetic*/ syntax to specify that the next synthesizable node
in a quasiliteral should be synthetic when produced in subst.


Other Changes in this CL
========================
Got rid of all the semicolon insertion warnings from
DefaultCajaRewriterTest's logs.

Fixed bug:  parser was expecting a semicolon after with-statements.


Open Questions
==============
Why do we need to ignore synthetic functions in determining in which
scope temporaries are declared?


Still TODO
==========
Define custom nodes for html event handlers and other code generators,
and get rid of the rules for Identifier and FunctionConstructor.




git-svn-id: https://google-caja.googlecode.com/svn/trunk@2085 360991c0-9f3b-0410-ba87-8b362a00edf4

faster ParseTreeNode visitor
http://codereview.appspot.com/6305076

ParseTreeNode has tree-walk methods called acceptPreOrder and
acceptPostOrder that are worst-case O(n) space and O(n**2) time.

The O(n) space is because ParseTreeNode does not have a link
to the node's parent, but some visitors want to know a node's
parent, so the tree-walker constructs a new AncestorChain object
to hold a node and its parent, then gives that AncestorChain to
the visitor.  This is wasted effort when a visitor doesn't care
about a node's parent.

The O(n**2) time is because the tree-walker tries to be robust
against mutations to the tree that affect the current node's
place in the tree, so before (or after) visiting each node,
it checks whether the node is still a child of the parent,
which requires a linear search of the parent's children list.

So, previously I had replaced one instance of acceptPreOrder
with a faster visitPreOrder method.

This patch expands on that, makes visitPreOrder faster and
simpler, and also uses it in more places.

A bunch of small changes to jbcsrc to speed up compilation.
* Extract constants for org.objectweb.asm.Type objects wherever possible.  Internally, these are represented as a String and so Type.getType(Class) does a bunch of string manipulation.  Promoting to constants amortizes this.
* Make ClassData no-longer be an @AutoValue.  @AutoValue by default clone()s primitive arrays on access (!) and so by not being an @AutoValue we can avoid a bunch of accidental buffer copies.
* Introduce a generic debug flag and use it to guard a bunch of checks in the compiler.  All of the checks are generally redundant with bytecode verification.  So now they will only be enabled in tests.

Use JsonReader internally rather than JsonParserJavacc.

For raw parsing (ie. new JsonParser().parse()) the parse time has improved substantially. For example, JsonParserJavacc parsed my 48KiB buzz feed in 4.8ms. JsonReader parses the same feed in 0.9ms.
